original:
Croatian interlace is a decorative art form that was originally characterized by vibrant colors, including red, blue, and yellow. While many of the wall paintings referenced in historical texts—such as the portraits of the Trpimirović dynasty located in the Church of St. George in Putalj, near Kaštel Sućurac—have not survived, they represent an early example of pre-Romanesque Croatian painting.
